<paragraph blockId="28.[151,1436,1940,2039]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
Monotypic genus represented by 
<taxonomicName authority="(Hershkovitz 1993)" baseAuthorityName="Hershkovitz" baseAuthorityYear="1993" box="[533,935,1940,1966]" class="Mammalia" family="Cricetidae" genus="Microakodontomys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="transitorius">
<emphasis box="[533,703,1941,1966]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">M. transitorius</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Hershkovitz, P." box="[720,927,1940,1966]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="1 - 18" refId="ref67972" refString="Hershkovitz, P. (1993) A new central brazilian genus and species of Sigmodontine rodent (Sigmodontinae) transitional between akodonts and oryzomyines, with a discussion of Muroid molar morphology and evolution. Fieldiana Zoology, 75, 1 - 18. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 3370" type="journal article" year="1993">Hershkovitz 1993</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, that inhabits the fringe zone between open grassland and bordering scrubland of the Brazilian Cerrado (
<bibRefCitation author="Hershkovitz, P." box="[819,1023,1976,2002]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="1 - 18" refId="ref67972" refString="Hershkovitz, P. (1993) A new central brazilian genus and species of Sigmodontine rodent (Sigmodontinae) transitional between akodonts and oryzomyines, with a discussion of Muroid molar morphology and evolution. Fieldiana Zoology, 75, 1 - 18. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 3370" type="journal article" year="1993">Hershkovitz 1993</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Prado, J. R. &amp; Percequillo, A. R." box="[1033,1324,1976,2002]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="1 - 120" refId="ref72147" refString="Prado, J. R. &amp; Percequillo, A. R. (2013) Geographic distribution of the genera of the tribe Oryzomyini (Rodentia: Cricetidae: Sigmodontinae) in South America: patterns of distribution and diversity. Archivos de Zoologia, 44 (1), 1 - 120. https: // doi. org / 10.11606 / issn. 2176 - 7793. v 44 i 1 p 1 - 120" type="journal article" year="2013">Prado &amp; Percequillo 2013</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Paresque, R. &amp; Hanson, J. D." pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="354 - 355" refId="ref70814" refString="Paresque, R. &amp; Hanson, J. D. (2015) Genus Microakodontomys Hershkovitz, 1993. In: Patton, J., Pardinas, U. F. J. &amp; D'Elia, G. (Eds.), Mammals of South America. 2. Rodents. University of Chicago Press, Chicago, Illinois, pp. 354 - 355." type="book chapter" year="2015">Paresque &amp; Hanson 2015</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="29.[151,1437,151,249]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
Karyotype: 2n = 38 and FN = 46. Autosomal complement: five small pairs of biarmed elements, and 13 acrocentric pairs decreasing in size. Sex chromosomes: X, a large submetacentric; Y, a small submetacentric, as mentioned by 
<bibRefCitation author="Paresque, R. &amp; Hanson, J. D." box="[263,570,222,249]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" pagination="354 - 355" refId="ref70814" refString="Paresque, R. &amp; Hanson, J. D. (2015) Genus Microakodontomys Hershkovitz, 1993. In: Patton, J., Pardinas, U. F. J. &amp; D'Elia, G. (Eds.), Mammals of South America. 2. Rodents. University of Chicago Press, Chicago, Illinois, pp. 354 - 355." type="book chapter" year="2015">Paresque &amp; Hanson (2015)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
